title: First woman leader of the Church of England confirmed in ancient ceremony | ABC NEWS
description: Sarah Mullally was officially confirmed as the first woman to lead the Church of England as Archbishop of Canterbury at a traditional ceremony in St Paul's Cathedral, London.  The vast cathedral was converted into a court of law for the ancient Confirmation of Election, a legal ceremony set within a church service marking the moment an archbishop-elect legally assumes office.  She took an oath of allegiance as the 106th Archbishop of Canterbury before senior bishops acting as royal commissioners under the authority of King Charles, and will also serve as the spiritual head of 85 million Christians across 165 countries in the global Anglican Communion.  Reporting via Reuters. To personalise your news & stay in the know, download the ABC News app through your app store. title: Airport security increased to prevent Nipah virus spread | The World | ABC NEWS
description: At least seven countries have introduced additional health screening at their borders to prevent the spread of Nipah virus from India. Travellers arriving in Bali and other major Asian airports have expressed relief at the swift response, comparing it to COVID-19 pandemic measures. title: Whales may be spared euthanasia after marine park exodus | The World | ABC NEWS
description: 30 captive beluga whales are looking for a new home after a marine park in Canada announced it could no longer afford to care for the animals.
